  "prompt": "Does the law differentiate between intentional and unintentional money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the law typically differentiates between intentional and unintentional money laundering. Intentional money laundering involves deliberate actions to conceal the source of illegally obtained funds, while unintentional money laundering may occur through negligence or lack of proper due diligence. The penalties and legal consequences can vary significantly based on intent.\n\nIntentional money laundering usually involves:\n- Deliberate attempts to hide illegal funds\n- Knowledge of the source of illegal money\n- Active participation in concealing financial transactions\n- Potential criminal charges with more severe penalties\n\nUnintentional money laundering might involve:\n- Accidental involvement in suspicious transactions\n- Lack of awareness about the source of funds\n- Failure to implement proper compliance procedures\n- Potential civil penalties or administrative sanctions\n\nThe specific legal treatment depends on jurisdiction and specific circumstances. Generally, intentional money laundering carries more serious criminal consequences, while unintentional cases may result in fines or regulatory actions.",
